args: Pinon arrives in Muskov, a town in the Osborne\nPrincipality, and begins her mission to find the\nlocation of the Church's dissident.
Sorry to make you help out\nwith the cleaning, traveler.
I do not mind; I am the outsider\nwho lost her way, after all.
Indeed, indeed. I certainly know what it's\nlike to be lost in unusual environs.
Are you also a stranger to this town?

I came here some six months ago, though
that's not an unusual tale in these parts;
nearly all the townspeople moved here
within the past year.
That seems odd for a town of this size.
Yes, Bishop Roalta has attracted\na great number of new residents.
He allows the people here to live far\nbetter lives than they have ever known.
He sounds like a fine man.
He is wonderful. So long as he is here,\nwe can leave all our cares behind.
A roof over our heads, bread on our plate,\nan honest day's work... All is provided for\nhere in Muskov. It's a true paradise!
And it is the bishop who arranges for you\nto have all of these things?
That's right. Oh, we're grateful to him,\nso we areâ€”he's nothing like those fools\nwho oversee the principality itself!
Speaking of which, it's time for Bishop\nRoalta to bless us with his daily sermon.\nYou should come lend your ear!
O children of Ilia, let us offer up a prayer\nto our beloved Goddess in the heavens.
(These people are near to\na state of frenzy...)
She shall protect our paradise from all\noutside enemies. All Her lost children\nwill be saved in equal measure.
Oh no! It's coming this way!\nEveryone, get back! I'll handle it!
She struck it down with a single blow!\nClearly, this is no ordinary traveler.\nCould she be...?
You there! Bring the black-garbed lady\nto me, that I might bandy words with her.
Hey, we're working here! We don't have\ntime to deal with the likes of you!
You didn't need to LITERALLY\nkick me out! Sheesh...

(They're a more disciplined bunch than
I expected. Guilty consciences, maybe?
Looks like there's something more to
this disappearing weapon after all...)
(Be that as it may, I can't force them to\ntalk when I'm not confident it'll lead to\nactual evidence.)
I was just trying to go to the mountain\nfor an adventure! Lemme gooooo!
Residents are not allowed to travel to\nneighboring towns without permission.\nNow do as you're told and go back home!
Must be my lucky day... You okay, kid?\nAll your bits and pieces in place?
Sure thing. But what's going on here?\nI heard some business about permission\nto visit a neighboring town?
Yeah, all the dumb soldiers started\nsayin' stuff like that a little while ago.
They say we can't go to the town across\nthe mountain because the dead are\nsummoning monsters or something.
I dunno anything. But all the adults keep\ntalking about how monsters are coming.
First, please permit me to thank you for\nprotecting the people of this town earlier.

I am honored you thought enough of it to
permit me this audience, Bishop Roalta.
Was there anything else you wished to
speak with me about?
Indeed, I have a request pertaining to\nthe monster you repelled earlier.
It is what we call the unknown creatures\nthat began appearing in our humble\ntown a short while ago.
We are at an utter loss as to what to do\nabout it; even the strongest among us\nseem powerless against them.
We were on the verge of surrender\nwhen you appeared and felled it with\nbut a single blow.
Clearly, you are a warrior of most\nprodigious skill and talent!
W-well, it's true I've trained in the bow\nsince I was little.
Would you use your skill to aid us and\ndefeat these monsters?
Surely it is the providence of heaven\nthat you have found your way to us.
Your good work will be appreciated\nmore than you can know.
(Though I didn't come here to fight\nmonsters, it could prove a useful chance\nto look into the bishop's movements...)
Very well. I accept your request.
Rest easy! I will give my all to the cause of\npeace in this town!
